               </msContents>
               <physDesc>
                  <p>Four books, probably put together for the present binding.</p>
                  <p>
                     <secFol><locus from="11" to="11">(fol. 11)</locus> -tudinem uituli</secFol>
                  </p>
                  <objectDesc form="codex">
                     <supportDesc material="perg">
                        <support>Parchment</support>
                        <extent>183 leaves (<seg type="leaf"><measure type="laterEndleaf" quantity="2">ii</measure> + <measure type="leaf" quantity="181">181</measure></seg>) <dimensions type="leaf" unit="mm">
                              <height>250</height>
                              <width>170</width>
                           </dimensions>
                           <note>The edges retrimmed and spattered with red.</note>
                        </extent>
                        <collation> A<hi rend="superscript">4</hi>(lacks 1), 1<hi rend="superscript">8</hi> / 2–6<hi rend="superscript">12</hi>, 7<hi rend="superscript">16</hi>, 8<hi rend="superscript">4</hi>(1 and 4 half-leaves) / 9–14<hi rend="superscript">12</hi>, 15<hi rend="superscript">10</hi>(7–10 canc.) / 16<hi rend="superscript">12</hi>; catchwords in II and III. </collation>
                     </supportDesc>
                  </objectDesc>
                  <bindingDesc>
                     <binding calendar="Gregorian" notAfter="1700" notBefore="1600">
                        <p>Standard Merton s. xvii, sewn on five bands; formerly chained from the usual position; fols. 180–1 are blank paper binding leaves. fol. i, formerly pasted down in an earlier binding, has the mark of a brass chain-staple at the foredge near the foot.</p>
                     </binding>
                  </bindingDesc>
               </physDesc>
               <history>
                  <provenance notAfter="1556">II was at the College by 1556: UO65. 183. </provenance>
                  <provenance>At the head of fol. 166 is a smudged and erased inscription: ‘[?Pertinet ad magistrum ... Chynnge]’. Perhaps <persName cert="low" key="person_4283" role="fmo">John Chynnge</persName> (<title>BRUO</title> 421), recorded as MA in 1449. </provenance>
                  <provenance>It is not clear when the rest of the book came to the College, prior to s. xvii in. Inside the front board is a sheet of paper with a table of contents s. xvii, and ‘N. 4. 5. Art:’, canc. in red. The College bookplate. ‘5’ is inked on the foredge.</provenance>
               </history>
